## The Empty Tier

The Empty Tier — introduced at 4ct where only three natural GIA cushion stones are available — continues at 5ct in a modified form. At 5ct, Blue Nile lists seven natural GIA Ideal-cut cushion diamonds. Seven sounds like more than three, but the range spans $71,271 to $177,928, and the quality grades available are narrow: six of the seven are G, F, or D colour at VS1 or VVS2 clarity. There is no E-VVS2 at 5ct. There is no H-VS2. The options that exist are the options — and the first available natural 5ct GIA cushion Ideal under $100,000 is a G-VS1 at $71,271.

[![Cushion cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire on white background](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/505021/505021_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**The Empty Tier at 5ct is structural, not cyclical.** At 5ct natural, the rough diamond market has fewer qualifying crystals per unit time than at 4ct — not because 5ct rough is rarer per se, but because the proportion of 5ct rough that yields a well-cut cushion modified brilliant at GIA Ideal quality with F-colour or better is extraordinarily small. Most 5ct natural cushion rough that reaches the retail market is G colour or lower, VS1 or VS2 clarity. The G-VS1 dominance of the 5ct natural table is not coincidental: G-VS1 is the grade combination where enough natural supply exists to populate a visible market tier.

**What The Empty Tier means for 5ct natural buyers.** Buy when a qualifying stone is available — do not wait for a better option at a better price. At 5ct natural cushion, there is no negotiating from a position of choice. If the [GIA 5.05ct G-VS1 Ideal at $71,271](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18306815?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) meets your quality requirements and budget, the purchase decision is binary: buy it now, or wait indefinitely for a stone that may or may not appear.

**The Empty Tier market anomaly at 5ct.** The natural 5ct entry ($71,271 for G-VS1) is lower than the natural 4ct entry ($85,685 for F-VS1). This appears to contradict the principle that larger stones cost more. The explanation: at 4ct, the available stock is F-VS1 minimum — there are no natural 4ct GIA Ideal cushions at G quality in Blue Nile's current inventory. At 5ct, the G-VS1 tier is represented, and G colour at any carat weight is priced lower than F colour. The lower 5ct entry versus 4ct entry reflects the colour grade available, not the carat weight economics.

