**Reading the natural 5ct table.** The [GIA 5.05ct G-VS1 Ideal at $71,271](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18306815?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the natural entry and the only stone available under $100,000. G colour at 5ct in yellow gold is visually indistinguishable from D — the large face-up area of 11mm does not make G colour more visible in warm metal; it makes the metal's colour reflection more significant, which works in G colour's favour in yellow or rose gold. VS1 clarity at 5ct natural in a cushion modified brilliant is reliably eye-clean without video verification required.

**The D-VS1 anomaly at 5ct natural.** The [GIA 5.02ct D-VS1 at $100,593](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29526665?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and [5.05ct D-VS1 at $177,928](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25679630?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are both D-VS1 Ideal — but one costs $77,335 more than the other. This price spread in the same grade combination reflects differences in proportions, depth percentage, table percentage, fluorescence, and other GIA report parameters not fully captured in the colour/clarity summary. At 5ct natural, two stones with the same GIA letter grades can differ dramatically in price because the sub-parameters that determine light performance and appearance vary significantly at this carat weight. Always request the full GIA report, not just the colour and clarity summary.

**Natural 5ct colour guidance.** G colour in yellow or rose gold at 5ct is the value-maximum choice — the colour savings versus D at 5ct natural are $30,000–$100,000+ depending on availability. In platinum or white gold, F colour is the minimum that ensures no visible body warmth at 11mm face-up. D colour at 5ct natural in white metal is the choice where the D grade on the certificate and the insurance documentation value of D colour matters — the visible difference from F in normal viewing is minimal.

> "The Empty Tier at 5ct natural has a nuance that buyers miss: the entry price at 5ct ($71,271 for G-VS1) is actually lower than the entry price at 4ct ($85,685 for F-VS1). Buyers who have been tracking natural cushion prices from 2ct upward often expect a monotonically increasing entry price. At 5ct, the G-VS1 is available because more natural rough yields G colour at 5ct than yields F colour — so the quality tier at the entry changes, and the price shifts accordingly. This is not a deal; it is a different quality tier at the same natural scarcity premium.
>
> The buyer who takes the 5ct G-VS1 in yellow gold for $71,271, believing it is a better value than the 4ct F-VS1 at $85,685, is actually comparing apples and oranges — the 5ct stone has lower colour grade and a larger face-up that amplifies any colour in white metal. In yellow gold at 5ct, G colour is perfect. In white gold at 5ct, the same stone shows warmth that the 4ct F-VS1 in white gold would not." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

