**The Lab Sovereign in action.** The IGI D-VVS1 at $10,157 and the GIA D-FL at $57,123 are both lab-grown cushion modified brilliants at 5ct with top colour and excellent clarity — but one costs $46,966 more than the other. The visible diamond quality at 11mm face-up is identical. The $46,966 difference purchases GIA documentation, FL clarity (invisible improvement over VVS1), and the GIA name on the certificate. For buyers who need none of those three specifically, the IGI D-VVS1 is the rational purchase. For buyers who need GIA documentation for insurance, estate, or professional appraisal purposes: the [GIA 4.95ct E-IF at $39,959](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27493672?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the GIA entry — E colour instead of D, but at $17,164 less than the GIA D-FL.

> "The Lab Sovereign at 5ct is the most important market structure concept in this guide because it changes the recommendation hierarchy that most buyers arrive with. Buyers who have been told — correctly — that GIA certification is preferable to IGI at 2ct and 3ct lab cushions often assume this holds at 5ct. It does not hold the same way. At 2ct, GIA and IGI lab prices are within $500–$1,000 of each other. At 5ct, the GIA lab premium is $29,802 versus the IGI entry. That is a qualitatively different decision. I am not telling buyers to distrust GIA at 5ct — GIA's grading is excellent. I am telling buyers to understand what they are paying $29,802 for, and to confirm they specifically need it.
>
> For most buyers at 5ct lab, IGI D-VVS1 at $10,157 is the purchase. GIA lab at $39,959 is for buyers who specifically need the GIA name on the document." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

