## 5ct Cushion Cut Diamond Clarity at 11mm Face-Up

At 11mm face-up, the cushion modified brilliant's light-scattering properties remain effective at concealing inclusions — but the rules for clarity selection tighten further compared to 4ct.

[![Cushion cut diamond solitaire engagement ring white gold pavé band](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501590/501590_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box5_001_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Natural 5ct clarity.** All six natural stones in the table above are VS1 or VVS2. This is The Empty Tier in action — the available natural 5ct cushion market has self-selected to VS1 and above. There are no VS2 or SI1 natural 5ct GIA Ideal cushions in Blue Nile's current inventory to consider. The clarity decision at 5ct natural is not "VS2 or VS1?" — it is "which VS1 stone, at what price?"

**Lab 5ct clarity.** The IGI D-VVS1 entry at $10,157 is the correct clarity choice. At $10,157 for VVS1, there is no financial argument for considering VS2 or SI1 lab cushions at 5ct — saving $1,000–$2,000 on a $10,157 stone to drop two clarity grades in a 5ct modified brilliant serves no buyer's interest. The clarity progression from D-VVS1 to D-IF ($30,186) and D-FL ($57,123) is purely certificatory at 5ct in a modified brilliant — IF and FL are not visible improvements over VVS1 at 11mm face-up under any normal viewing condition.

**The Crushed Ice Trap at 5ct.** At 11mm face-up, the cushion modified brilliant's crushed ice pattern — which distributes light uniformly across the entire face-up surface — reaches its maximum expression. The 5ct modified brilliant is the brightest, most uniformly white-light-reflecting configuration in the cushion market, and it is also the configuration with the least visible individual fire. Buyers who arrive at 5ct expecting the large surface area to amplify the stone's fire are experiencing The Crushed Ice Trap at its most intense scale. At 5ct, if fire is the priority — distinct, coloured flashes of rainbow dispersion under dim lighting — the cushion brilliant sub-type (not modified) is mandatory. If uniform, photogenic brightness across 11mm face-up is the goal: the modified brilliant delivers exactly that.

---

## 5ct Elongated Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

The 5ct elongated cushion cut diamond ring — length-to-width ratio of 1.15:1 to 1.30:1, approximately 12.5mm × 10mm — is the most dramatic finger-coverage configuration in the cushion market. A 5ct elongated cushion covers nearly the full width of most fingers from edge to edge, creating a ring presence that approaches fashion jewellery territory in terms of visual impact.

At 5ct elongated, the length-to-width ratio choice matters more than at smaller sizes. A 1.15:1 ratio at 5ct (approximately 11.5mm × 10mm) creates a soft rectangular outline close to the square cushion. A 1.30:1 ratio (approximately 12.5mm × 9.5mm) creates a distinctly elongated form that closely resembles an oval from across a room. For buyers drawn to the elongated cushion at 5ct: the 1.15–1.20 range provides the cushion's soft-cornered character with moderate elongation; the 1.25–1.30 range delivers maximum finger coverage and oval-adjacent proportions.

The elongated 5ct cushion and the 5ct oval diamond are frequently compared. The oval at 5ct has higher optically efficient light return and more visible fire than an elongated cushion modified brilliant at the same carat weight. The elongated cushion has a softer, more vintage outline and the modified brilliant's uniform brightness. At 5ct lab, both are available at accessible price points — the choice is purely aesthetic. For the complete elongated sub-type guide, see the [elongated cushion cut diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond).

---

## 5ct Cushion Cut Engagement Ring Settings

At 5ct, setting selection carries structural weight in addition to aesthetic meaning. The center stone at 11mm face-up and approximately 5ct of mass requires settings engineered for long-term stability, not merely attractive appearance.

[![Cushion cut diamond pavé engagement ring white gold four-prong flat lay](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/502820/502820_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box5_001_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Solitaire at 5ct.** The 5ct cushion solitaire is the setting that communicates maximum restraint and maximum stone confidence simultaneously. At 11mm face-up, the stone is large enough that any additional setting elements — halos, pavé, split shanks — compete rather than complement. A four-prong solitaire at 5ct allows the full 121mm² of face-up surface to read without visual interruption. The structural consideration: the shank must be heavy enough to balance the stone's mass. A 2.5mm–3mm shank width is appropriate for a 5ct cushion solitaire — thinner shanks risk distortion over time under the stone's weight.

**Halo at 5ct.** The 5ct cushion halo is the most dramatically large ring configuration in mainstream jewellery. The halo extends the 11mm face-up stone to approximately 13–15mm in total visual diameter — a size that covers adjacent fingers on most hands below ring size 7. Before selecting a halo at 5ct, try the total setting size in person. A 5ct cushion halo in yellow gold on a ring size 8+ hand is an extraordinary, intentional statement. On a ring size 5 hand, it may be physically uncomfortable for daily wear.

**5ct cushion solitaire versus halo.** The solitaire communicates "this stone is exceptional and needs no enhancement." The halo communicates "this ring is a statement piece that uses every available tool." Both are valid at 5ct. The choice is character, not quality: solitaire buyers want the stone to be the singular object of attention; halo buyers want the ring as a complete visual composition.

For complete setting analysis and prong configuration guidance at 5ct, see the [cushion cut engagement ring guide](/cushion-cut-diamond-engagement-ring).

**Split shank at 5ct.** The split shank at 5ct creates an architectural frame that references the square cushion outline through the two parallel metal strands below the center stone. At 5ct, the split shank also addresses the visual mass problem: the split shank's wider profile below the stone creates structural continuity between the large center and the ring's band in a way that a simple solitaire shank does not. The visual transition from the stone to the band is graduated rather than abrupt.

[![Cushion cut diamond split shank engagement ring yellow gold](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/502620/502620_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

---

## Metal Choice for a 5ct Cushion

Metal choice at 5ct amplifies its effect compared to smaller sizes because the 11mm stone reflects more metal colour into its pavilion across a larger surface area.

**Platinum or 18K white gold.** The correct choice for D-E colour lab cushions where the D/E colour grade is to be maximised visually. At 11mm face-up, a D colour lab cushion in white metal reads as the most perfectly colourless diamond presentation available. For the [IGI 5ct D-VVS1 at $10,157](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27641932?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), platinum or 18K white gold provides the visual context that makes D colour meaningful at the scale of 11mm.

**Yellow gold.** The correct choice for G colour natural cushions at 5ct. The [GIA 5.05ct G-VS1 Ideal at $71,271](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18306815?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in 18K yellow gold reads as visually colourless — the warm metal reflection neutralises G colour body warmth in the same way it does at 3ct and 4ct, but at 5ct the neutralisation is even more effective because more of the pavilion surface is exposed to the warm metal reflection. Yellow gold at 5ct is not a compromise for G colour buyers; it is the optimal metal choice.

**Rose gold.** Rose gold at 5ct is the choice for buyers who want the highest contrast between the stone's white brilliance and the metal's warmth. At 11mm face-up, a D colour lab cushion against 18K rose gold creates a distinctly luxurious, fashion-forward aesthetic. For F colour natural cushions in rose gold at 5ct: the warm metal may reveal slight body warmth in F at this face-up size. Choose E colour or above for rose gold at 5ct natural.

---

## 5ct Lab vs Natural: The Case Closes Completely

At 5ct, the financial comparison between lab and natural reaches numbers that make the case with complete clarity:

- Lab IGI D-VVS1 5ct: $10,157
- Natural GIA G-VS1 5ct: $71,271
- Difference: $61,114 — and the lab stone is three colour grades better (D vs G) and equivalent in clarity

The lab stone is better on every stated quality grade AND costs $61,114 less. At 5ct, the natural diamond does not win on any quality metric relative to the lab alternative at the entry price. The natural stone's only advantage is natural origin — the fact that a geological process over billions of years created this specific crystal, rather than a CVD reactor over weeks. That origin story has value to buyers who value it. The price of that story at 5ct is $61,114.

**Choose lab at 5ct if:** The $61,114 saving is meaningful to your financial life, and you have examined the natural origin question honestly without external pressure. The [IGI 5ct D-VVS1 at $10,157](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27641932?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the rational choice for virtually every buyer who is not specifically committed to natural origin.

**Choose natural at 5ct if:** You have a non-negotiable, examined preference for natural origin that you would maintain even after full consideration of the $61,114 alternative use of that money. You are purchasing as an heirloom investment where natural certification and origin documentation will matter to future generations. You have a specific professional, cultural, or values-based reason for natural origin that is independent of any social expectation or marketing. The [GIA 5.05ct G-VS1 Ideal at $71,271](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18306815?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in yellow gold is the natural entry that delivers the most quality per dollar at 5ct natural. Buy when it is in stock.


